Predicting Used Car Prices

Part 1: Exploratory Data Analysis

Background:

The Indian market is currently witnessing a significant surge in the demand for used cars. This trend has been fueled by a slowdown in new car sales, prompting consumers to turn towards the pre-owned vehicle market. Over the past few years, the size of this market has not only grown but has also surpassed that of new cars. Cars4U, an emerging tech startup, is strategically positioning itself to capitalize on these market dynamics.

The pricing and supply of new cars are generally predictable, controlled by Original Equipment Manufacturers (OEMs), with the only variations occurring due to dealership-level discounts at the final stage of the customer journey. However, the used car market operates differently. It is characterized by significant uncertainties in both pricing and supply. The valuation of a used car can be influenced by multiple factors including mileage, model year, brand, and overall condition. For sellers, setting an accurate price is challenging yet crucial for market competitiveness.

Objective:

The primary goal of this data sience project is to develop a robust pricing model that can accurately predict the prices of used cars. Such a model will not only facilitate fair market transactions but also enable Cars4U to implement differential pricing strategies that could drive profitability and market growth.

2. Univariate analysis

Univariate analysis is used to explore each variable in a data set, separately. It looks at the range of values, as well as the central tendency of the values. It can be done for both numerical and categorical variables.

2.1 Numerical data

Histograms and box plots help to visualize and describe numerical data. We use box plot and histogram to analyse the numerical columns. First, I write a function that will help me create a boxplot and histogram for any input numerical variable. This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots and histograms for the variable.

In[]:
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(12, 8), bins=50, title=""):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (15, 10))
    bins: number of bins (default 50)
    title: Title of the figure (default is empty for flexibility)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid
                                           sharex=True,  # X-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.25, .75)},
                                           figsize=figsize)  # Creating the 2 subplots
    
    sns.boxplot(x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet')  # Boxplot with a symbol for mean
    sns.histplot(x=feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, color="blue")  # For histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='green', linestyle='--')  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-')  # Add median to the histogram

    if title:  # Only set the title if one is provided
        plt.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

KM_driven - kilometers driven

  • Examine and treat the extreme outlier
    • A car manufactured as recently as 2017 registering 6,5 million under kilometers driven is near impossible. The car would need to drive 8900 km everyday in order to reach 6,5 million in 2 years.
    • It can be considered as data entry error so we can remove this value/entry from data.
  • Create histogram and boxplot visualizations to study the distribution of KM_driven
  • Kilometers_Driven is highly right-skewed
  • Apply log transformation:
    • Typically statistical and machine learning models assume that the data is normally distributed. We use log transformation, which is commonly used for right-skewed distributions. It helps compress large values more than smaller values, thereby pulling the tail in.

Histogram:

  • Appears multi-modal with several peaks (possibly bimodal).
  • Majority of the data points are concentrated around 15- 25 mileage units
  • The distribution is right-skewed. Models built on such skewed data may be biased towards higher values and might not perform well across the entire range of mileage. The log transformation reduces this skewness, making the data more suitable for linear regression models, among others.

Boxplot:

  • There are several outliers, especially on the higher end of the mileage scale.
  • The median (indicated by the green triangle in the boxplot) is near 20, aligning well with the center of the histogram's dominant peaks.
In[]:
Mileage_log = clean_df['Mileage']
histogram_boxplot(np.log(Mileage_log), title="Mileage_log")

  • Normality: The log transformation has made the distribution more symmetric, which is closer to a normal distribution. The log transformation has compressed the data, making the distribution more symmetrical and reducing the positive skew. The tail on the right side, which represented high mileage values in the original distribution, is now less prominent.

  • Scale: The log transformation also helps in managing the scale of the data, bringing large values closer together. This can help in improving the numerical stability of the model.

2.2 Categorical data

I pre-define a function to help with barplots that indicate the percentage for each category. This function takes the categorical column as the input and returns the barplots for the variable.

In[]:
def perc_on_bar(z):
    total = len(clean_df[z])  # Total number of data points
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
    
    # Get the actual counts of the categories in 'z'
    counts = clean_df[z].value_counts().reset_index()
    counts.columns = ['category', 'counts']  # Renaming for clarity
    
    # Create the count plot using 'category' for both x and hue, applying a colorful palette
    ax = sns.barplot(x='category', y='counts', hue='category', data=counts, palette='viridis', dodge=False)
    #ax.legend().set_visible(False)  # Hiding the legend

    for p in ax.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        percentage = '{:.2f}%'.format(100 * height / total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
        y = height
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=12, ha='center', va='bottom')

    plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate labels for better readability
    plt.show()

4. Feature Engineering

  1. First I filter out the rows where price data is not available. For model construction we only need entries with the Price value is available. Otherwise we cannot evaluate the performance of the model.
  2. Then, I extract the Brand and Model data from the Name variable
  3. Impute the missing Mileage values based on the average mileage value of cars with similar Brand, Model and Engine
  4. Impute the missing Seats values based on the average value of cars with similar Brand and Model
  5. Impute the missing Engine values based on the average of cars with similar Brand, Model and Mileage
  6. Impute the missing Power values based on the average of cars with similar Brand, Model and Engine
  7. Drop the New_price variable, because of too many missing values.

Clean the 'Name' column:

In[]:
def clean_name(name):
    # Remove 'New' and any of the specified fuel types, case insensitive, possibly within brackets
    name = re.sub(r'\bnew\b', '', name, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    name = re.sub(r'\b(cng|diesel|petrol|lpg|electric)\b', '', name, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    name = re.sub(r'\s*\((cng|diesel|petrol|lpg|electric)\)\s*', '', name, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    # Replace number followed by 'Series' with a hyphen in between
    name = re.sub(r'(\d+)\s+(series)', r'\1-\2', name, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    # Remove number and 'seater'
    name = re.sub(r'\d+-seater', '', name, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    name = re.sub(r'\d+\s+seater', '', name, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    # Remove all instances of parentheses
    name = re.sub(r'[()]', '', name)
    # Additional cleaning to strip extra spaces and correct the formatting
    name = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', name).strip()
    
    return name

output_df['Cleaned_Name'] = output_df['Name'].apply(clean_name)
In[]:
# Extract the first and second words for Brand and Model
output_df['Brand'] = output_df['Cleaned_Name'].str.split().str.get(0)
output_df['Model'] = output_df['Cleaned_Name'].str.split().str.get(1)

Mileage variable

Replace missing values with the average mileage of cars from the same Brand, Model and Year

In[]:
# Calculate the mean 'Mileage' for each 'Brand', 'Model', 'Engine' group, excluding zeros and NaNs
group_means = output_df[(output_df['Mileage'] != 0) & (output_df['Mileage'].notna())].groupby(['Brand', 'Model', 'Engine'])['Mileage'].mean()

# If 'Engine' is missing use only Mileage
brand_model_means = output_df[(output_df['Mileage'] != 0) & (output_df['Mileage'].notna())].groupby(['Brand', 'Model'])['Mileage'].mean()
overall_mean = output_df[(output_df['Mileage'] != 0) & (output_df['Mileage'].notna())]['Mileage'].mean()

# Apply the corrected mileage values
def get_corrected_mileage(row):
    if row['Mileage'] == 0 or np.isnan(row['Mileage']):
        if pd.notna(row['Engine']):
            # Try to get the group mean, if unavailable, fallback to brand/model mean, then overall mean
            return group_means.get((row['Brand'], row['Model'], row['Engine']), 
                                   brand_model_means.get((row['Brand'], row['Model']), overall_mean))
        else:
            # Fallback to brand/model mean, then overall mean
            return brand_model_means.get((row['Brand'], row['Model']), overall_mean)
    else:
        return row['Mileage']

output_df['Mileage'] = output_df.apply(get_corrected_mileage, axis=1)

print(f'Remaining rows with zero Mileage: {output_df[output_df["Mileage"] == 0].shape[0]}')
print(f'Missing values in Mileage after update: {output_df["Mileage"].isna().sum()}')

Seats variable

  • Now, we can use the information in Brand and Model columns to impute the missing values.
  • We will replace the missingSeats values with the median of cars with similar Brand and Model.
In[]:
def impute_seats(series):
    if series.isna().all():
        return series  # Return the series as is if all values are NaN 
    else:
        return series.fillna(series.median())

output_df['Seats'] = output_df.groupby(['Brand', 'Model'])['Seats'].transform(impute_seats)
seats_na = output_df[output_df['Seats'].isna()]

Engine column

  • We impute these missing values based on the average value of cars with similar Brand, Model and Mileage.
    • As we know cars with similar Brand+Model, Mileage tend to have similar engines.
    • If a specific Brand + Model + Mileage group is not available, then I use only Brand + Model average
    • There are 36 missing values in the Engine column
  • To improve the distribution of values, we apply log transformation to Engine column as well
In[]:
# Calculate the mean 'Engine' for each 'Brand', 'Model', 'Mileage' group
engine_means = output_df[output_df['Engine'].notna()].groupby(['Brand', 'Model', 'Mileage'])['Engine'].mean()
# use only 'Brand' + 'Model', if 'Mileage' is missing or the specific group mean is not available  
brand_model_engine_means = output_df[output_df['Engine'].notna()].groupby(['Brand', 'Model'])['Engine'].mean()

def get_corrected_engine(row):
    if pd.isna(row['Engine']):
        # Try to get the group mean based on Brand, Model, Mileage; if unavailable, fallback to Brand, Model
        return engine_means.get((row['Brand'], row['Model'], row['Mileage']),
                                brand_model_engine_means.get((row['Brand'], row['Model']), np.nan))
    else:
        return row['Engine']

Power variable

In[]:
# Calculate mean 'Power' for different groupings
power_means_engine = output_df[output_df['Power'].notna()].groupby(['Brand', 'Model', 'Engine'])['Power'].mean()
power_means_model_engine = output_df[output_df['Power'].notna()].groupby(['Model', 'Engine'])['Power'].mean()
power_means_model = output_df[output_df['Power'].notna()].groupby(['Model'])['Power'].mean()
power_means_mileage = output_df[output_df['Power'].notna()].groupby(['Mileage'])['Power'].mean()

def get_corrected_power(row):
    if pd.isna(row['Power']):
        # Try to get the group mean based on Brand, Model, Engine
        power_with_engine = power_means_engine.get((row['Brand'], row['Model'], row['Engine']), np.nan)
        if pd.isna(power_with_engine):
            # Try Model + Engine
            power_model_engine = power_means_model_engine.get((row['Model'], row['Engine']), np.nan)
            if pd.isna(power_model_engine):
                # Try Model only
                power_model = power_means_model.get(row['Model'], np.nan)
                if pd.isna(power_model):
                    # Finally, use Mileage
                    return power_means_mileage.get(row['Mileage'], np.nan)
                else:
                    return power_model
            else:
                return power_model_engine
        else:
            return power_with_engine
    else:
        return row['Power']

output_df['Power'] = output_df.apply(get_corrected_power, axis=1)

remaining_missing_power = output_df['Power'].isna().sum()
print(f'Remaining missing values in Power column: {remaining_missing_power}')

Remaining missing values in Power column: 0
